{"title_page": "Kilrea", "text_new": "{{other uses of}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place  \n  |official_name=     Kilrea\n  |irish_name=        Cill Ria\n  |static_image_name = Kilrea_-_geograph.org.uk_-_342208.jpg\n  |map_type=          Northern Ireland\n  |coordinates = {{coord|54.966667|-6.583333|display=inline,title}}\n  |label_position= none\n| population = 2,724\n| population_ref = <small>([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011&nbsp;Census]])\n  |irish_grid_reference= \n  |unitary_northern_ireland= [[Causeway Coast and Glens]]\n  |country=           Northern Ireland\n  |post_town=         COLERAINE\n  |postcode_area=     BT\n  |postcode_district= BT51\n  |dial_code=         028\n  |constituency_westminster=  [[East Londonderry (UK Parliament constituency)|East Londonderry]]\n  |constituency_ni_assembly= [[East Londonderry (Assembly constituency)|East Londonderry]]\n  |lieutenancy_northern_ireland= [[County Londonderry]]\n  |website=       \n  |belfast_distance= \n  |hide_services= yes\n}}\n\n'''Kilrea''' ({{IPAc-en|k|\u026a|l|\u02c8|r|e\u026a}} {{respell|kil|RAY}}, {{Irish derived place name|Cill Ria|church on the hill}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.placenamesni.org/resultsdetail.phtml?entry=1761|title=Placenames NI|author=|date=|website=placenamesni.org|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727150852/http://www.placenamesni.org/resultsdetail.phtml?entry=1761|archive-date=27 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/58282.aspx|title=Cill Ria/Kilrea|author=|date=|website=Logainm.ie|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> is a village, [[townland]] and [[Civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] in [[County Londonderry]], [[Northern Ireland]]. It gets its name from the ancient church that was located near to where the current Church of Ireland is located on Church Street looking over the town. It is near the [[River Bann]], which marks the boundary between County Londonderry and [[County Antrim]]. In the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]] it had a population of 2,724 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ninis2.nisra.gov.uk/public/AreaProfileReportViewer.aspx?FromAPAddressMulipleRecords=Kilrea@Exact|title=statistics|first=Northern Ireland Statistics and Research|last=Agency|date=|website=www.ninis2.nisra.gov.uk|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> It is situated within [[Causeway Coast and Glens]] district.\n\n== History ==\nThere is a tradition that [[St Patrick]] visited the area during the fifth century, a story repeated recently in the book 'The Fairy Thorn' produced by Kilrea local historians. Today Kilrea is a market town and commercial centre of the surrounding district. The village is centred on 'The Diamond' which includes the town's War Memorial erected in honour of Kilrea men killed in the [[World War I|Great War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ulsterwarmemorials.net/html/kilrea.html|title=Ulster War Memorials|author=|date=|website=ulsterwarmemorials.net|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820055609/http://www.ulsterwarmemorials.net/html/kilrea.html|archive-date=20 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The village is featured in the song ''Kitty the rose of Kilrea'' by The Irish Rover band.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n=== The Troubles ===\nA total of seven people died in violence relating to [[the Troubles]]. Five were killed by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) and two by the [[Ulster Freedom Fighters]] (UFF). All the IRA's victims were current or former members of the security forces, with two belonging to the [[Royal Ulster Constabulary]], one a current and one a former member of the [[Ulster Defence Regiment]], and one belonging to the [[British Territorial Army]]. All were [[Protestant]]s and three of the five were off duty when they were killed. According to the Sutton Index of Deaths, both men killed by the UFF were former members of the IRA. At the time of their deaths both were associated with [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. Both were [[Catholic]]. Of the seven killed in the Kilrea Troubles, all were killed in separate incidents and all were shot except one of the RUC officers, who was killed by a [[booby trap]] bomb while on patrol. While deaths in many other areas were concentrated in the early 1970s, in Kilrea they were spread between 1976 and 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/index.html|title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths - menu page|first=Malcolm|last=Sutton|date=|website=cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Festival of the Fairy Thorn ===\nA feature of Kilrea is its 'Fairy Thorn' tree. It is the focal point of the annual summer cross-community festival in the town.<ref>[http://www.discovernorthernireland.com/Kilrea-Coleraine-Kilrea-Coleraine-P14076 Kilrea, Coleraine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624094910/http://www.discovernorthernireland.com/Kilrea-Coleraine-Kilrea-Coleraine-P14076 |date=2010-06-24 }} [[Northern Ireland Tourist Board]] website</ref>\n\n== Notable People ==\n* [[Martin O'Neill]], ex professional footballer and ex-manager of Nottingham Forest FC\n* [[John Dallat]], first nationalist mayor of the Borough of Coleraine\n* [[Monica McWilliams]], academic and former politician\n\n==Railways==\n[[Kilrea railway station]] was opened by the [[Derry Central Railway]] on 18 February 1880.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kilrea station | work=Railscot - Irish Railways | url=http://www.railscot.co.uk/Ireland/Irish_railways.pdf | accessdate=2012-04-29}}</ref> It was taken over by the [[Northern Counties Committee]] in September 1901.\n\nThe station closed to passengers on 28 August 1950 by the [[Ulster Transport Authority]].\n\n== Sport ==\n[[File:The Kilrea Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 279711.jpg|thumb|right|[[River Bann|Bann]] Bridge at Kilrea]]\n* Kilrea Angling Club\n* Kilrea Camogie Club\n* Kilrea Golf Club\n* [[Kilrea GAC|Kilrea P\u00e1draig Pearses GAC]]\n* Kilrea United Football Club\n* Manor Golf and Sports Club\n* Go Pro Kart Racing Movanagher Road\n* Kilrea Sports Complex\n\n== Education ==\n* Kilrea Primary School\n* St Columba's Primary School\n* St Paul's College\n* Crossroads Primary School\n\n== Religion ==\n[[File:First Kilrea Presbyterian Church - geograph.org.uk - 342207.jpg|thumb|right|[[First Kilrea Presbyterian Church]]]]\n* Boveedy Presbyterian Church\n* [[First Kilrea Presbyterian Church]]\n* Kilrea Baptist Church\n* Second Kilrea Presbyterian Church\n* St Anne's Roman Catholic Church<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derrydiocese.org/kilrea.asp|title=Kilrea Parish - Derry Diocese, Ireland|author=|date=|website=derrydiocese.org|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231133940/http://www.derrydiocese.org/kilrea.asp|archive-date=31 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* St Patrick's [[Church of Ireland]]\n* St. Mary\u2019s Roman Catholic Church\n[[File:Drumnagarner RC Church - geograph.org.uk - 840133.jpg|thumb|Drumnagarner Catholic church.]]\n\n== 2011 Census ==\nKilrea is classified as an Intermediate Settlement by the [http://www.nisra.gov.uk/ NI Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA)] (i.e., with population between 2,250 and 4,500 people). On Census day (22 March 2011) there were 2,724 people living in Kilrea. Of these:\n* 23.27% were aged under 16 years and 14.5% were aged 60 and over\n* 50.77% of the population were male and 49.23% were female\n* 67.11% were from a [[Catholic]] background and 29.77% were from a [[Protestantism|Protestant]] background\n* 6.46% of people aged 16\u201374 were unemployed\n\nFor more details see the [http://www.ninis2.nisra.gov.uk/public/AreaProfileReportViewer.aspx?FromAPAddressMulipleRecords=Kilrea@Exact match of location name: @Exact Match Of Location Name:  Kilrea@4?]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of civil parishes of County Londonderry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{County Londonderry}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in County Londonderry]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes of County Londonderry]]\n[[Category:Causeway Coast and Glens district]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses of}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place  \n  |official_name=     Kilrea\n  |irish_name=        Cill Ria\n  |static_image_name = Kilrea_-_geograph.org.uk_-_342208.jpg\n  |map_type=          Northern Ireland\n  |coordinates = {{coord|54.966667|-6.583333|display=inline,title}}\n  |label_position= none\n| population = 2,724\n| population_ref = <small>([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011&nbsp;Census]])\n  |irish_grid_reference= \n  |unitary_northern_ireland= [[Causeway Coast and Glens]]\n  |country=           Northern Ireland\n  |post_town=         COLERAINE\n  |postcode_area=     BT\n  |postcode_district= BT51\n  |dial_code=         028\n  |constituency_westminster=  [[East Londonderry (UK Parliament constituency)|East Londonderry]]\n  |constituency_ni_assembly= [[East Londonderry (Assembly constituency)|East Londonderry]]\n  |lieutenancy_northern_ireland= [[County Londonderry]]\n  |website=       \n  |belfast_distance= \n  |hide_services= yes\n}}\n\n'''Kilrea''' ({{IPAc-en|k|\u026a|l|\u02c8|r|e\u026a}} {{respell|kil|RAY}}, {{Irish derived place name|Cill Ria|church on the hill}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.placenamesni.org/resultsdetail.phtml?entry=1761|title=Placenames NI|author=|date=|website=placenamesni.org|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727150852/http://www.placenamesni.org/resultsdetail.phtml?entry=1761|archive-date=27 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/58282.aspx|title=Cill Ria/Kilrea|author=|date=|website=Logainm.ie|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> is a village, [[townland]] and [[Civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] in [[County Londonderry]], [[Northern Ireland]]. It gets its name from the ancient church that was located near to where the current Church of Ireland is located on Church Street looking over the town. It is near the [[River Bann]], which marks the boundary between County Londonderry and [[County Antrim]]. In the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]] it had a population of 2,724 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ninis2.nisra.gov.uk/public/AreaProfileReportViewer.aspx?FromAPAddressMulipleRecords=Kilrea@Exact|title=statistics|first=Northern Ireland Statistics and Research|last=Agency|date=|website=www.ninis2.nisra.gov.uk|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> It is situated within [[Causeway Coast and Glens]] district.\n\n== History ==\nThere is a tradition that [[St Patrick]] visited the area during the fifth century, a story repeated recently in the book 'The Fairy Thorn' produced by Kilrea local historians. During the [[Plantation of Ulster]] Kilrea and the surrounding [[townlands]] were granted to the [[Worshipful Company of Mercers]] by [[King James I]] for settlement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.from-ireland.net/derry/lewis/kilrea.htm|title=Lewis's Topographical Directory of Ireland, 1837|author=|date=|website=from-ireland.net|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206033353/http://www.from-ireland.net/derry/lewis/kilrea.htm|archive-date=6 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Their headquarters in Ulster were at nearby Movanagher on the banks of the River Bann. Today Kilrea is a market town and commercial centre of the surrounding district. The village is centred on 'The Diamond' which includes the town's War Memorial erected in honour of Kilrea men killed in the [[World War I|Great War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ulsterwarmemorials.net/html/kilrea.html|title=Ulster War Memorials|author=|date=|website=ulsterwarmemorials.net|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820055609/http://www.ulsterwarmemorials.net/html/kilrea.html|archive-date=20 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The village is featured in the [[Orange Institution|Orange]] song, Sprigs of Kilrea. It is also mentioned in the song ''Kitty the rose of Kilrea'' by The Irish Rover band.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n=== The Troubles ===\nA total of seven people died in violence relating to [[the Troubles]]. Five were killed by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) and two by the [[Ulster Freedom Fighters]] (UFF). All the IRA's victims were current or former members of the security forces, with two belonging to the [[Royal Ulster Constabulary]], one a current and one a former member of the [[Ulster Defence Regiment]], and one belonging to the [[British Territorial Army]]. All were [[Protestant]]s and three of the five were off duty when they were killed. According to the Sutton Index of Deaths, both men killed by the UFF were former members of the IRA. At the time of their deaths both were associated with [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. Both were [[Catholic]]. Of the seven killed in the Kilrea Troubles, all were killed in separate incidents and all were shot except one of the RUC officers, who was killed by a [[booby trap]] bomb while on patrol. While deaths in many other areas were concentrated in the early 1970s, in Kilrea they were spread between 1976 and 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/index.html|title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths - menu page|first=Malcolm|last=Sutton|date=|website=cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Festival of the Fairy Thorn ===\nA feature of Kilrea is its 'Fairy Thorn' tree in the grounds of [[First Kilrea Presbyterian Church]]. It is the focal point of the annual summer cross-community festival in the town.<ref>[http://www.discovernorthernireland.com/Kilrea-Coleraine-Kilrea-Coleraine-P14076 Kilrea, Coleraine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624094910/http://www.discovernorthernireland.com/Kilrea-Coleraine-Kilrea-Coleraine-P14076 |date=2010-06-24 }} [[Northern Ireland Tourist Board]] website</ref>\n\n== Notable People ==\n* [[Martin O'Neill]], ex professional footballer and ex-manager of Nottingham Forest FC\n* [[John Dallat]], first nationalist mayor of the Borough of Coleraine\n* [[Monica McWilliams]], academic and former politician\n\n==Railways==\n[[Kilrea railway station]] was opened by the [[Derry Central Railway]] on 18 February 1880.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kilrea station | work=Railscot - Irish Railways | url=http://www.railscot.co.uk/Ireland/Irish_railways.pdf | accessdate=2012-04-29}}</ref> It was taken over by the [[Northern Counties Committee]] in September 1901.\n\nThe station closed to passengers on 28 August 1950 by the [[Ulster Transport Authority]].\n\n== Sport ==\n[[File:The Kilrea Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 279711.jpg|thumb|right|[[River Bann|Bann]] Bridge at Kilrea]]\n* Kilrea Angling Club\n* Kilrea Camogie Club\n* Kilrea Golf Club\n* [[Kilrea GAC|Kilrea P\u00e1draig Pearses GAC]]\n* Kilrea United Football Club\n* Manor Golf and Sports Club\n* Go Pro Kart Racing Movanagher Road\n* Kilrea Sports Complex\n\n== Education ==\n* Kilrea Primary School\n* St Columba's Primary School\n* St Paul's College\n* Crossroads Primary School\n\n== Religion ==\n[[File:First Kilrea Presbyterian Church - geograph.org.uk - 342207.jpg|thumb|right|[[First Kilrea Presbyterian Church]]]]\n* Boveedy Presbyterian Church\n* [[First Kilrea Presbyterian Church]]\n* Kilrea Baptist Church\n* Second Kilrea Presbyterian Church\n* St Anne's Roman Catholic Church<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derrydiocese.org/kilrea.asp|title=Kilrea Parish - Derry Diocese, Ireland|author=|date=|website=derrydiocese.org|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231133940/http://www.derrydiocese.org/kilrea.asp|archive-date=31 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* St Patrick's [[Church of Ireland]]\n* St. Mary\u2019s Roman Catholic Church\n[[File:Drumnagarner RC Church - geograph.org.uk - 840133.jpg|thumb|Drumnagarner Catholic church.]]\n\n== 2011 Census ==\nKilrea is classified as an Intermediate Settlement by the [http://www.nisra.gov.uk/ NI Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA)] (i.e., with population between 2,250 and 4,500 people). On Census day (22 March 2011) there were 2,724 people living in Kilrea. Of these:\n* 23.27% were aged under 16 years and 14.5% were aged 60 and over\n* 50.77% of the population were male and 49.23% were female\n* 67.11% were from a [[Catholic]] background and 29.77% were from a [[Protestantism|Protestant]] background\n* 6.46% of people aged 16\u201374 were unemployed\n\nFor more details see the [http://www.ninis2.nisra.gov.uk/public/AreaProfileReportViewer.aspx?FromAPAddressMulipleRecords=Kilrea@Exact match of location name: @Exact Match Of Location Name:  Kilrea@4?]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of civil parishes of County Londonderry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{County Londonderry}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in County Londonderry]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes of County Londonderry]]\n[[Category:Causeway Coast and Glens district]]\n", "name_user": "86.165.41.183", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory:Typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilrea"}
